    "# Mean Reversion on Equities: Exploration of Statistical Arbitrage Fundamentals and Finding Alpha Using the Ornstein-Ulhenbeck Process in Technology Stocks"

    "\n",
    "## Problem Identification \n",
    "\n",
    "The stock market is a jungle full of mysteries. If you think about what is actually going on in the stock market at an intra-day to day to day level, you will quickly realize that the market is not \"effocient\". An \"efficient\" market, is what we use in finance to describe a market that where all participants have equal access to all possible resources involving all trading activities. This situation should create a trading environment where all participants have equal opportunities, and theoretically, with perfect (efficient) executions, there shouldn't be any arbitrage available for anyone to take advantage of. Arbitrage itself is what we call for profits made that are not based on real change in value, but rather taking advantage\n",
    "\n",
    "Despite the growth in efficiency by the push of the digital revolution in finance, the market is still full of inefficiencies, and the imbalance widespread access of endo/exo-sources easily available to the market like news,social media, analyst's recommendations often triggers slight to massive anomalous movements in the market. \n",
    "\n",
    "This project will explore this idea, by proposing a method that allows us to identify those anomali, and take advantage of it by utilizing the beautiful combination of mathematics, statistics, machine learning, and finance, to create a decision making machine\n",
    " "
   ]

    "## 2. Methodology"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "\n",
    "In the academic world, movement in asset prices used to be widely accepted as random, and it is impossible to predict. But we as practicioners in finance knows that stock movements being random is the last thing that we thought of when we think of where the price will be.\n",
    "\n",
    "In more recent studies though, different models have been used and researched. One of the model that I agree with is the following: \n",
    "\n",
    "stock_value = linear time series from value*  + random walk (trader's psychology) + environmental factors\n",
    "\n",
    "  *(for blue-chips, non-linear for pennies)\n",
    "\n",
    "The idea here is to first model anomalies in the market using a robust quantitative method, we start with a linear time series first for each stocks taken into account. For this, I used a PCA factor comprising of 10 tech ETFs and model it with regression.\n",
    "\n",
    "This results in a pretty solid base model where each model for each stock on average have an r2 of ~ .6 - .7\n",
    "\n",
    "This is our base model now from the regression: \n",
    "\n",
    "s(t) = α + β * PCA + Residual\n",
    "\n",
    "We are interested in the residual, because it reflects how this particular stock's movement in value differs from other similar stocks in the same sector. To model it, we use the ornstein-ulhenbeck process.\n",
    "\n",
    "Let r(t) be the residual of s(t), The change in stock price with respect to the residual for each time point will be defined by the change in the residual at t - (t-1).\n",
    "\n",
    "and hence s(t) = α + β * PCA + dr(t) + env. factors.\n",
    "\n",
    "The O-U process can then be defined as the following\n",
    "where\n",
    "\n",
    "dr(t) = α(r) + k ( mu - r(t) ) dt + σ dW(t), k>0\n",
    "\n",
    "where mu is the mean residual, k is the speed of mean reversion (acceleration of change in residual), and (mu-r(t)) itself is the deviation of the last residual from the mean. σ is the instant volatility at time t, which for change in residual can be regarded as 0, and dw(t) is a random walk\n",
    "\n",
    "by that assumption, dr(t) = k ( mu - r(t)) dt, and s(t) = α + β * PCA + α(r) + k( mu - r(t)) + env factors              \n",
    "where lim α(r) -> inf = mu\n",
    "\n",
    "This is an auto-regressive, stationary process which can be estimated using a rolling ar-1 model. We used a 60 days window for the rolling arima and regression to then estimate k.\n",
    "\n",
    "After we finalize our model, we can detect anomaly based on the speed of mean reversion and the current residual's deviation from the mean. This will be our signal. When the deviation is large, we regard them as anomalous.\n",
    "\n",
    "The signal model is simple and highly related to the z-score concept, let's call this s-score\n",
    "\n",
    "where s-score = (r(t) - mu)/ σ(eq)\n",
    "\n",
    "where σ(eq) is the equilibrium variance of the supposed model, and can be calculated as σ(eq) = σ(r) * (2*k)^(-0.5)\n",
    "\n",
    "From here, what a trader do with the signal have limitless potential. What I do for the backtest on this project is by calculating the optimum buying/selling point on each stock (maximum Sortino), using the Bayesian's optimization, for each day on a 60 days window, and use that signal to make trading decisions."
   ]
  },
